    {
      "id": "/page/0/TextInlineMath/3",
      "block_type": "TextInlineMath",
      "html": "<p block-type=\"TextInlineMath\">We present two defining properties of subexponential distribution functions. Let <math display=\"inline\">(X_k)_{k \\in \\mathbb{N}}</math> be independently and identically distributed positive random variables with distribution function <math display=\"inline\">F</math> such that <math display=\"inline\">F(x) &lt; 1</math> for all <math display=\"inline\">x &gt; 0</math>. Denote by <math display=\"inline\">\\overline{F}(x) = 1 - F(x)</math>for <math display=\"inline\">x \\ge 0</math>, the tail of F, and for <math display=\"inline\">n \\in \\mathbb{N}</math>,</p>",
      "page": 206,
      "polygon": [
        [
          74.9367088607595,
          375.5009940357853
        ],
        [
          285.73828125,
          375.5009940357853
        ],
        [
          285.73828125,
          444.005859375
        ],
        [
          74.9367088607595,
          444.005859375
