      "html": "<p block-type=\"TextInlineMath\">The classical insurance risk model is the <i>Cram´er—</i> <i>Lundberg model</i> (cf. [2, 4, 6, 8] and <i>see</i> <b>Ruin The</b><b>ory</b>), where the <i>claim times</i> occur at the jump times of a Poisson<i>(λ)</i> process <i>(N (t))t</i><sup>≥</sup><sup>0</sup> (<i>see</i> <b>Poisson Process</b>) and the claims <i>(Xk</i> <i>)k</i><sup>∈</sup> are again an independently and identically distributed sequence with finite mean. The <i>risk process</i> is for <i>initial reserve</i> <i>u</i> ≥ 0 and <i>pre</i><i>mium rate</i> <i>c &gt;</i> 0 defined as</p>",
